'''Susan Diane Wojcicki''' ({{IPAc-en|w|uː|ˈ|tʃ|ɪ|t|s|k|i}} {{respell|woo|CHITS|kee}};<ref>{{YouTube|a07s88y7f-k|"#DearMe: Susan Wojcicki, CEO of YouTube"}}</ref> July 5, 1968 – August 9, 2024) was an American business executive who was the [[chief executive officer]] of [[YouTube]] from 2014 to 2023. Her net worth was estimated at $765&nbsp;million in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/susan-wojcicki|title=#34 Susan Wojcicki|website=Forbes|access-date=July 9, 2022|language=en|archive-date=August 23, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210823074616/https://www.forbes.com/profile/susan-wojcicki|url-status=live}}</ref>

Wojcicki worked in the [[technology industry]] for over twenty years.<ref>{{Cite web|date=August 10, 2019|title=YouTube's Susan Wojcicki: 'Where's the line of free speech – are you removing voices that should be heard?'|url=http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/aug/10/youtube-susan-wojcicki-ceo-where-line-removing-voices-heard|access-date=January 16, 2021|website=the Guardian|language=en|archive-date=January 19, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119032309/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/aug/10/youtube-susan-wojcicki-ceo-where-line-removing-voices-heard|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Connley|first=Courtney|date=August 20, 2019|title=YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki: Here's what to say when men are talking over you at a meeting|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/20/susan-wojcicki-what-to-say-when-men-are-talking-over-you-at-a-meeting.html|access-date=January 16, 2021|website=CNBC|language=en|archive-date=November 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109180450/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/20/susan-wojcicki-what-to-say-when-men-are-talking-over-you-at-a-meeting.html|url-status=live}}</ref> She became involved in the creation of [[Google]] in 1998 when she rented out her garage as an office to the company's founders.<ref>"In the Plex" by Steven Levy, page 34</ref> She worked as Google's first [[marketing manager]] in 1999, leading the company's online advertising business and original video service. After observing the success of YouTube, she suggested that Google should buy it; the deal was approved for $1.65&nbsp;billion in 2006. She was appointed CEO of YouTube in 2014, serving until resigning in February 2023.<ref name=":1" />

== Early life and education ==
Susan Diane Wojcicki was born in [[Santa Clara, California]], on July 5, 1968, the daughter of [[Esther Wojcicki]], an American journalist, and [[Stanley Wojcicki]], a Polish physics professor at [[Stanford University]].<ref name="NYT">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/10/business/susan-wojcicki-dead.html|title=Susan Wojcicki, Former Chief of YouTube, Dies at 56|first1=John|last1=Yoon|first2=Mike|last2=Isaac|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 10, 2024|accessdate=August 10, 2024|url-access = limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/39461?c=search&first=Susan&last=Wojcicki |title=California Births, 1905–1995 |publisher=Familytreelegends.com |access-date=March 15, 2014 |archive-date=June 4, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604041118/http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/39461?c=search&first=Susan&last=Wojcicki |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/18/how-the-wojcickis-parents-raised-23andme-founder-youtube-ceo.html|title=How Anne and Susan Wojcicki's parents raised the founder of 23andMe and the CEO of YouTube|last=Clifford|first=Catherine|date=June 18, 2018|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=May 14, 2019|archive-date=January 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103010613/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/18/how-the-wojcickis-parents-raised-23andme-founder-youtube-ceo.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Her maternal grandparents were [[History of the Jews in Russia|Russian Jewish]] immigrants.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tramiel|first1=Preeva|title=Esther Wojcicki: A Jewish mother of the tech revolution|url=https://jwa.org/blog/esther-wojcicki-jewish-mother-of-tech-revolution|access-date=August 1, 2017|archive-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119122055/https://jwa.org/blog/esther-wojcicki-jewish-mother-of-tech-revolution|url-status=live}}</ref> Her paternal grandfather, [[Franciszek Wójcicki]], was a Polish politician who was elected MP during the [[1947 Polish legislative election]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Parlamentarzyści – Pełny opis rekordu|url=https://bs.sejm.gov.pl/F?func=find-b&request=000008719&find_code=SYS&local_base=ARS10|access-date=December 31, 2021|website=bs.sejm.gov.pl|archive-date=May 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240513021355/https://bs.sejm.gov.pl/F?func=find-b&request=000008719&find_code=SYS&local_base=ARS10|url-status=live}}</ref> Her paternal grandmother, [[Janina Wójcicka Hoskins]], was a Polish-American librarian at the [[Library of Congress]] and was responsible for building the largest collection of Polish material in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zalewski|first=Wojciech|date=October 1, 2011|title=Janina Wójcicka Hoskins (1912–1996): Portrait of an Esteemed Librarian|journal=Slavic & East European Information Resources|volume=12|issue=4|pages=224–236|doi=10.1080/15228886.2011.623117|s2cid=144135260|issn=1522-8886}}</ref> She had two sisters: Janet, a doctor of anthropology and epidemiology,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sellers|first1=Patricia|title=Before Google, the Wojcicki girls learned from Mom|url=http://fortune.com/2012/02/01/before-google-the-wojcicki-girls-learned-from-mom/|website=Fortune.com|access-date=December 16, 2014|archive-date=February 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207040836/http://fortune.com/2012/02/01/before-google-the-wojcicki-girls-learned-from-mom/|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Anne Wojcicki|Anne]], an entrepreneur who is the co-founder and CEO of [[23andMe]].<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/08/i-raised-2-successful-ceos-and-a-doctor-here-is-one-if-the-biggest-mistakes-parents-make.html I raised 2 successful CEOs and a doctor—here's one of the biggest mistakes I see parents making] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905230316/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/08/i-raised-2-successful-ceos-and-a-doctor-here-is-one-if-the-biggest-mistakes-parents-make.html |date=September 5, 2019}}, Esther Wojcicki, Published Wed, May 8, 2019, cnbc.com.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/18/how-the-wojcickis-parents-raised-23andme-founder-youtube-ceo.html|title=How Anne and Susan Wojcicki's parents raised the founder of 23andMe and the CEO of YouTube|last=Clifford|first=Catherine|date=June 18, 2018|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=October 28, 2019|archive-date=January 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103010613/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/18/how-the-wojcickis-parents-raised-23andme-founder-youtube-ceo.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Wojcicki grew up on the Stanford campus, where mathematical scientist [[George Dantzig]] was her neighbor.<ref name="fastcompany2014a" /> She attended [[Gunn High School]] in [[Palo Alto, California]], and wrote for the school newspaper.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://fortune.com/2012/02/01/before-google-the-wojcicki-girls-learned-from-mom/ |title=Before Google, the Wojcicki girls learned from Mom |magazine=Fortune Magazine |date=February 1, 2012 |first=Patricia |last=Sellers |access-date=October 4, 2014 |archive-date=February 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207040836/http://fortune.com/2012/02/01/before-google-the-wojcicki-girls-learned-from-mom/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Her first business was selling "spice ropes" door-to-door at the age of eleven. A humanities major in college, she took her first [[computer science]] class as a senior.<ref name=":0" /> She studied history and literature at [[Harvard University]] and graduated with honors in 1990. She originally planned on getting a PhD in economics and pursuing a career in academia but changed her plans when she discovered an interest in technology.<ref name="fastcompany2014a" /> She also received her MS in economics in 1993 from the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] and an MBA in 1998 from the [[UCLA Anderson School of Management]].<ref name="mercurynews2011">{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_17286427 |title=Susan Wojcicki: The most important Googler you've never heard of |newspaper=San Jose Mercury News |date=February 7, 2011 |first=Mike |last=Swift |access-date=October 4, 2014 |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817045904/http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_17286427 |url-status=live}}</ref>

== Career ==

=== Before Google ===
Before becoming Google's first marketing manager in 1999, Wojcicki worked in marketing at [[Intel Corporation]] in [[Santa Clara, California]],<ref name="fastcompany2014a">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3033957/the-woman-behind-the-superlatives-three-things-you-need-to-know-about-susan-wojcicki |title=The Woman Behind the Superlatives: Three Things You Need to Know About Susan Wojcicki |magazine=The Fast Company |date=August 6, 2014 |first=Nicole |last=Laporte |access-date=October 4, 2014 |archive-date=August 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818215114/http://www.fastcompany.com/3033957/the-woman-behind-the-superlatives-three-things-you-need-to-know-about-susan-wojcicki |url-status=live}}</ref> and was a management consultant at [[Bain & Company]] and at R.B. Webber & Company.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://ideas.time.com/contributor/susan-wojcicki/ |title=Susan Wojcicki |magazine=Time |access-date=October 4, 2014 |archive-date=March 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314183002/http://ideas.time.com/contributor/susan-wojcicki/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Google ===
Wojcicki was Google employee #16. In September 1998, the same month that Google was incorporated, co-founders [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] set up the Google office in Wojcicki's garage in [[Menlo Park, California]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=April 2, 2012 |title=Our history in depth – Company – Google |newspaper= |url=http://www.google.com/intl/en/about/company/history/ |url-status=deviated |access-date=November 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402210041/http://www.google.com/intl/en/about/company/history/ |archive-date=April 2, 2012}}</ref> Wojcicki was introduced to the pair through a mutual friend around the time she was newly married and struggling to afford the mortgage on her recent house purchase.<ref name="ma20240810">{{Cite web |last=Ma |first=Jason |date=August 10, 2024 |title=See what Google's original office looked like when it started in Susan Wojcicki's garage |url=https://fortune.com/2024/08/10/google-original-office-1998-susan-wojcicki-garage-larry-page-sergey-brin/ |work=Fortune |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240811013911/https://fortune.com/2024/08/10/google-original-office-1998-susan-wojcicki-garage-larry-page-sergey-brin/ |archive-date=August 11, 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> Page and Brin would use Wojcicki's garage as their office for $1,700 a month.<ref name="NYT" /> They later converted three small ground-floor bedrooms into additional workspaces to accommodate their growing team.<ref name="ma20240810" /> At Google, she worked on the initial viral marketing programs, helped create the company's longtime logo with designer [[Ruth Kedar]], and spearheaded the first [[Google Doodle]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/alumni/100-inspirational-alumni/susan-wojcicki-inspirational-100-alumna|title=Susan Wojcicki – "Inspirational 100" Alumna|publisher=UCLA Anderson School of Management|access-date=October 4, 2014|archive-date=March 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304201849/http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/alumni/100-inspirational-alumni/susan-wojcicki-inspirational-100-alumna|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NCvdUbeWS60C&q=susan+wojcicki+At+Google%2C+she+worked+on+the+initial+viral+marketing+programs%2C+as+well+as+the+first+Google+Doodles&pg=PA15|title=Think Quarterly: Innovation (US)|language=en|access-date=October 20, 2020|archive-date=May 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210515075745/https://books.google.com/books?id=NCvdUbeWS60C&q=susan+wojcicki+At+Google,+she+worked+on+the+initial+viral+marketing+programs,+as+well+as+the+first+Google+Doodles&pg=PA15|url-status=live}}</ref> She also co-developed and launched [[Google Images|Google Image Search]] with engineer Huican Zhu.

In 2003, Wojcicki was the first product manager of one of Google's seminal advertising products—[[Google AdSense|AdSense]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Profile Of Susan Wojcicki: Mother Of AdSense|url=https://searchengineland.com/profile-of-susan-wojcicki-mother-of-adsense-11629 |first1=Barry |last1=Schwartz |date=July 5, 2007|website=Search Engine Land|access-date=May 31, 2020|archive-date=May 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200516121341/https://searchengineland.com/profile-of-susan-wojcicki-mother-of-adsense-11629|url-status=live}}</ref> She earned the Google Founders' Award in recognition for this work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/techinvestor/corporatenews/2007-07-04-google-wojcicki_N.htm|title=The house that helped build Google |website=USA TODAY |first1=Jefferson |last1=Graham |date=2007 |access-date=November 23, 2019|archive-date=September 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926095339/https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/techinvestor/corporatenews/2007-07-04-google-wojcicki_N.htm|url-status=live}}</ref> Wojcicki was subsequently promoted to Google's senior vice president of Advertising & Commerce, and oversaw the company's advertising and [[web analytics|analytic]] products, including [[AdWords]], [[AdSense]], [[DoubleClick]], and [[Google Analytics]].<ref name="mercurynews2011" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Gustin|first=Sam|title=Google Ad Chief Susan Wojcicki: 'The Book Isn't Finished'|url=https://www.wired.com/epicenter/2011/05/susan-wojcicki/ |url-access=limited |access-date=September 10, 2011|newspaper=Wired |date=May 3, 2011|archive-date=September 6, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906185040/http://www.wired.com/epicenter/2011/05/susan-wojcicki/|url-status=live}}</ref>

YouTube, then a small start-up, was successfully competing with Google's Google Video service, overseen by Wojcicki. She had recommended and subsequently managed the $1.65&nbsp;billion purchase of YouTube in 2006.<ref name="mercurynews2011" />

=== YouTube ===
In February 2014, Wojcicki became the CEO of YouTube.<ref>{{cite news|last=Orescovic|first=Alexi|title=Google taps longtime executive Wojcicki to head YouTube|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/us-google-youtube-idINBREA141Y420140205|work=Reuters|date=February 5, 2014|access-date=July 5, 2021|archive-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406005302/https://in.reuters.com/article/us-google-youtube-idINBREA141Y420140205|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/02/05/susan-wojcicki-youtube/ |website=TechCrunch |first1=Ryan |last1=Lawler |title=Google Ads SVP Susan Wojcicki Takes Over At YouTube|date=February 5, 2014 |access-date=June 12, 2014|archive-date=June 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626235401/http://techcrunch.com/2014/02/05/susan-wojcicki-youtube/|url-status=live}}</ref> She was named "the most important person in advertising",<ref>{{Cite web |url-access=subscription |website=Adweek |first1=Tim |last1=Peterson |title=Is This the Most Important Person in Advertising?|date=February 25, 2013 |url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/most-important-person-advertising-147489/|access-date=January 8, 2021|language=en-US|archive-date=January 10, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210110213850/https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/most-important-person-advertising-147489/|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as named one of [[Time 100|''Time''{{'s}} 100 most influential people]] in 2015<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Grazer |first=Brian |url=http://time.com/3822770/susan-wojcicki-2015-time-100/ |title=The 100 Most Influential People: Susan Wojcicki |magazine=Time |date=April 16, 2015 |access-date=October 5, 2015 |archive-date=October 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019030051/http://time.com/3822770/susan-wojcicki-2015-time-100/ |url-status=dead}}</ref> and described in a later issue of ''Time'' as "the most powerful woman on the Internet."<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Luscombe |first=Belinda |url=https://time.com/4012832/meet-youtubes-view-master/ |title=Meet YouTube's Viewmaster |magazine=Time |date=August 27, 2015 |access-date=October 5, 2015 |archive-date=May 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514202227/http://time.com/4012832/meet-youtubes-view-master/ |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2014, she had joined the board of [[Salesforce]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Susan Wojcicki|url=https://www.salesforce.com/company/leadership/bios/bio-wojcicki/|access-date=September 18, 2020|website=Salesforce.com|language=en|archive-date=September 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200917172454/https://www.salesforce.com/company/leadership/bios/bio-wojcicki/|url-status=live}}</ref> She also served on the board of [[Room to Read]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Board of Directors|url=https://www.roomtoread.org/leadership-board/board-of-directors/|access-date=September 18, 2020|website=www.roomtoread.org|archive-date=October 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201028000034/https://www.roomtoread.org/leadership-board/board-of-directors/|url-status=live}}</ref> an organization that focuses on literacy and gender equality in education, and was a board member of [[UCLA Anderson School of Management]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Susan Wojcicki ('89) – "The most important Googler you've never heard of"|url=https://blogs.anderson.ucla.edu/anderson/2011/02/susan-wojcicki-89-the-most-important-googler-youve-never-heard-of.html|access-date=September 18, 2020|website=UCLA Anderson School of Management Blog|archive-date=May 17, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210517204708/https://blogs.anderson.ucla.edu/anderson/2011/02/susan-wojcicki-89-the-most-important-googler-youve-never-heard-of.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Mateusz Morawiecki wraz z Susan Wojcicki prezesem YouTube odwiedzili Centrum Nauki Kopernik.jpg|thumb|Wojcicki next to Polish Prime Minister [[Mateusz Morawiecki]] in [[Warsaw]] in November 2018]]
After Wojcicki became the CEO of YouTube, the company reached 2 billion logged-in users a month<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2019/02/05/youtube-2-billion-monthly-users/|title=YouTube Hits 2 Billion Monthly Users, As Number Of Channels With 1 Million Subscribers Doubled Last Year|date=February 5, 2019|website=Tubefilter|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2019|archive-date=April 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402043200/https://www.tubefilter.com/2019/02/05/youtube-2-billion-monthly-users/|url-status=live}}</ref> and users were watching one billion hours of content a day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/27/youtube-one-billion-hours-of-video-daily/#hs1RRV4k_Sqx|title=YouTube just hit a huge milestone|last=Hamedy|first=Saba|work=Mashable|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en|archive-date=December 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201222213421/https://mashable.com/2017/02/27/youtube-one-billion-hours-of-video-daily/#hs1RRV4k_Sqx|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2017/06/23/youtube-1-5-billion-monthly-users-mobile-video/|title=YouTube Claims 1.5 Billion Monthly Users in Latest Ad Sales Pitch|work=Fortune|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en|archive-date=October 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027025421/http://fortune.com/2017/06/23/youtube-1-5-billion-monthly-users-mobile-video/|url-status=live}}</ref> By 2021, YouTube had paid more than $30 billion to creators, artists, and media companies.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Letter from Susan: Our 2021 Priorities|url=https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/letter-from-susan-our-2021-priorities/|access-date=December 24, 2021|website=blog.youtube|language=en-us|archive-date=December 23, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211223170515/https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/letter-from-susan-our-2021-priorities/|url-status=live}}</ref> There are localized versions of YouTube in 100 countries around the world across 80 languages. From her appointment as CEO up to August 2017, YouTube's percentage of female employees rose from 24 to nearly 30 percent.<ref name="Wojcicki">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/03/how-to-break-up-the-silicon-valley-boys-club-susan-wojcicki|title=Exclusive: How to Break Up the Silicon Valley Boys' Club|last=Wojcicki|first=Susan|work=The Hive|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en|archive-date=August 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818055811/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/03/how-to-break-up-the-silicon-valley-boys-club-susan-wojcicki|url-status=live}}</ref> Wojcicki also emphasized new YouTube applications and experiences designed to cater to users interested in family<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/02/23/hands-on-with-youtube-kids-googles-newly-launched-child-friendly-youtube-app/|title=Hands On With "YouTube Kids," Google's Newly Launched, Child-Friendly YouTube App|last=Perez|first=Sarah|work=TechCrunch|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en|archive-date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626223616/https://techcrunch.com/2015/02/23/hands-on-with-youtube-kids-googles-newly-launched-child-friendly-youtube-app/|url-status=live}}</ref> gaming,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/aug/26/youtube-gaming-live-website-apps|title=Google launches YouTube Gaming to challenge Amazon-owned Twitch|last=Dredge|first=Stuart|date=August 26, 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=September 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906044745/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/aug/26/youtube-gaming-live-website-apps|url-status=live}}</ref> and music<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/11/12/9723496/youtube-music-app-offline-background|title=YouTube Music is here, and it's a game changer|work=The Verge|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en-US|archive-date=October 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027025337/https://www.theverge.com/2015/11/12/9723496/youtube-music-app-offline-background|url-status=live}}</ref> content. While CEO, the company developed 10 forms of monetization for YouTube creators, including channel memberships, merchandise, BrandConnect, and paid digital goods like Super Chat.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=10 ways to monetize on YouTube|url=https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/10-ways-monetize-youtube/|url-status=live|access-date=May 31, 2020|website=YouTube Blog|language=en|archive-date=August 3, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210803200146/https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/10-ways-monetize-youtube/}}</ref> She also launched YouTube's advertisement-free subscription service, [[YouTube Premium]] (formerly known as YouTube Red),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/10/21/google-wants-you-to-pay-9-99-per-month-for-ad-free-youtube/|title=Google wants you to pay $9.99 per month for ad-free YouTube {{!}} VentureBeat|website=venturebeat.com|language=en-US|access-date=October 26, 2017|date=October 22, 2015|archive-date=March 8, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308075506/https://venturebeat.com/2015/10/21/google-wants-you-to-pay-9-99-per-month-for-ad-free-youtube/|url-status=live}}</ref> and its [[Over-the-top media services|over-the-top]] (OTT) internet television service [[YouTube TV]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-39124092|title=YouTube takes on cable with new service|last=Lee|first=Dave|date=March 1, 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en-GB|archive-date=March 8, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308103826/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-39124092|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2020, the company launched [[YouTube Shorts]], its short-form video experience,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Building YouTube Shorts, a new way to watch & create on YouTube|url=https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/building-youtube-shorts/|access-date=December 28, 2021|website=blog.youtube|language=en-us|archive-date=June 10, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210610013637/https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/building-youtube-shorts/|url-status=live}}</ref> which surpassed 50 billion daily views in February 2023.<ref>{{cite news |title=Google says YouTube Shorts has crossed 50 billion daily views |author=Ivan Mehta |date=February 3, 2023 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2023/02/03/google-says-youtube-shorts-has-crossed-50-billion-daily-views/ |access-date=February 7, 2023 |archive-date=February 7, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230207064102/https://techcrunch.com/2023/02/03/google-says-youtube-shorts-has-crossed-50-billion-daily-views/ |url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2022, YouTube publicized that the company had surpassed 80 million Music and Premium subscribers, including trailers.<ref>{{cite web |title=We hit 80 million?! |author=Lyor Cohen |date=November 9, 2022 |url=https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/youtube-music-premium-80-million-lyor-cohen/ |accessdate=February 7, 2023 |archive-date=November 20, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221120105515/https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/youtube-music-premium-80-million-lyor-cohen/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The company also reported over 100 billion hours of global gaming content watched on the platform in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|title=2020 is YouTube Gaming's biggest year, ever: 100B watch time hours|url=https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/youtube-gaming-2020/|access-date=December 28, 2021|website=blog.youtube|language=en-us|archive-date=December 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208152602/https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/youtube-gaming-2020/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Wojcicki tightened YouTube's policy on videos it regards as potentially violating its policies on hate speech and violent extremism.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=An update on our commitment to fight violent extremist content online|url=https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/an-update-on-our-commitment-to-fight/|access-date=May 31, 2020|website=YouTube Blog|language=en-US|archive-date=August 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200808070643/https://blog.youtube/news-and-events/an-update-on-our-commitment-to-fight|url-status=live}}</ref> The more stringent policies came after ''[[The Times]]'' showed that "ads sponsored by the British government and several private sector companies had appeared ahead of YouTube videos supporting terrorist groups" and several large advertisers withdrew their ads from YouTube in response.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alba|first=Davey|author-link=Davey Alba|title=YouTube's Ad Problems Finally Blow Up in Google's Face|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/03/youtubes-ad-problems-finally-blow-googles-face|newspaper=WIRED|date=March 25, 2017|access-date=September 4, 2017|archive-date=September 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905052907/https://www.wired.com/2017/03/youtubes-ad-problems-finally-blow-googles-face|url-status=live}}</ref> The enforcement policies have been criticized as censorship.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hern|first=Alex|title=To censor or not to censor? YouTube's double bind|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/mar/21/youtube-advertisers-censorship|newspaper=theguardian|date=March 21, 2017|access-date=August 29, 2017|archive-date=August 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808155124/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/mar/21/youtube-advertisers-censorship|url-status=live}}</ref> YouTube has also faced criticism that the company applies its enforcement policies inconsistently, with larger content creators treated more favorably. During the controversy surrounding [[Logan Paul]]'s YouTube video about a person who died of suicide, Wojcicki said that Paul did not violate YouTube's [[wikt:three strikes and you're out|three-strike]] policy, and therefore did not meet the criteria for being banned from the platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/12/17006074/youtube-ceo-logan-paul-susan-wojcicki|title=YouTube's CEO says Logan Paul doesn't deserve to be kicked off the platform|last=Newton|first=Casey|date=February 12, 2018|website=The Verge|access-date=October 18, 2018|archive-date=October 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018122247/https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/12/17006074/youtube-ceo-logan-paul-susan-wojcicki|url-status=live}}</ref>

Wojcicki has emphasized educational content as a priority for the company, and on July 20, 2018, announced the initiative YouTube Learning, which invests in grants and promotion to support education focused creator content.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=Mid-year update on our five creator priorities for 2018|url=https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/mid-year-update-on-our-five-creator/|url-status=live|access-date=May 31, 2020|website=YouTube Blog|archive-date=August 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200804030912/https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/mid-year-update-on-our-five-creator}}</ref>

On October 22, 2018, Wojcicki wrote that Article 13, as written in the [[Copyright Directive|European Union Copyright Directive]], would make YouTube directly liable for copyrighted content, and poses a threat to content creators' ability to share their work.<ref>{{Cite web|title=A final update on our priorities for 2018|url=https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/a-final-update-on-our-priorities-for/|access-date=December 8, 2021|website=blog.youtube|language=en-us|archive-date=December 8, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208065714/https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/a-final-update-on-our-priorities-for/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On February 16, 2023, Wojcicki announced her resignation from YouTube via a company blog post. She said she wanted to focus on "family, health, and personal projects" but would be taking on an advisory role across Google and its parent company [[Alphabet Inc.|Alphabet]].<ref name=":1">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2023/02/16/youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-says-shes-stepping-down.html|title=YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki says she's stepping down|last=Elias|first=Jennifer|date=February 16, 2023|website=CNBC|access-date=February 16, 2023|archive-date=May 20, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230520221059/https://www.cnbc.com/2023/02/16/youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-says-shes-stepping-down.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/youtube-ceo-wojcicki-steps-down-2023-02-16/|title=YouTube CEO Wojcicki, one of the first Google employees, steps down|last=<!--Not stated-->|first=<!--Not stated-->|date=February 16, 2023|website=Reuters|access-date=February 16, 2023|archive-date=February 16, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230216175940/https://www.reuters.com/technology/youtube-ceo-wojcicki-steps-down-2023-02-16/|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Advocacy ==
Wojcicki was an advocate for several causes, including the expansion of paid family leave,<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/susan-wojcicki-paid-maternity-leave-is-good-for-business-1418773756|title=Paid Maternity Leave Is Good for Business|last=Wojcicki|first=Susan|date=December 16, 2014|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=October 26, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-date=May 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513234213/https://www.wsj.com/articles/susan-wojcicki-paid-maternity-leave-is-good-for-business-1418773756|url-status=live}}</ref> the plight of [[Syrian refugees]],<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://time.com/4373471/susan-wojcicki-world-refugee-day/|title=Susan Wojcicki: Refugees Are Trying to Escape Terror—Not Create It|magazine=Time|access-date=October 26, 2017|archive-date=August 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830050457/http://time.com/4373471/susan-wojcicki-world-refugee-day/|url-status=live}}</ref> countering gender discrimination at technology companies,<ref name="Wojcicki" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/09/technology/youtube-ceo-gender-discrimination-response/index.html|title=YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki on gender discrimination: It still hurts|last=Isidore|first=Chris|work=CNNMoney|access-date=October 26, 2017|archive-date=October 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027025656/http://money.cnn.com/2017/08/09/technology/youtube-ceo-gender-discrimination-response/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> getting young girls interested in computer science, and prioritizing computer programming and coding in schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/susan-wojcicki/tech-industry-gender-gap_b_9089472.html|title=Closing the Tech Industry Gender Gap|last=Wojcicki|first=Susan|date=January 27, 2016|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=October 26, 2017|archive-date=August 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821021254/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/susan-wojcicki/tech-industry-gender-gap_b_9089472.html|url-status=live}}</ref> She also owned a real estate holding company that worked on the sustainable growth of [[Los Altos, California]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=August 10, 2024 |title=Ex-YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki, who succumbed to lung cancer, was the woman behind Google's switch to video streaming |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/technology/susan-wojcicki-the-woman-who-made-google-take-up-video-streaming/article68509587.ece |access-date=August 11, 2024 |work=[[The Hindu]] |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X |archive-date=August 11, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240811001123/https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/technology/susan-wojcicki-the-woman-who-made-google-take-up-video-streaming/article68509587.ece |url-status=live }}</ref> Wojcicki endorsed [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. presidential election]].<ref>Mandelbaum, R., [https://www.forbes.com/sites/robbmandelbaum/2016/09/23/more-business-leaders-sign-on-with-clinton/#4d1ff10750b0n More Business Leaders Sign On With Clinton] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010204503/http://www.forbes.com/sites/robbmandelbaum/2016/09/23/more-business-leaders-sign-on-with-clinton/#4d1ff10750b0n |date=October 10, 2016}}, ''Forbes'', September 23, 2016.</ref>

== Personal life and death ==
Wojcicki married Dennis Troper, a director of product management at Google, in [[Belmont, California]], on August 23, 1998.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/community_pulse/1998_Nov_11.WEDDI111.html |title=Weddings |newspaper=Palo Alto Weekly |date=November 11, 1998 |access-date=October 4, 2014 |archive-date=January 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130082515/http://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/community_pulse/1998_Nov_11.WEDDI111.html |url-status=live}}</ref> They had five children.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |title=Susan Wojcicki |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/susan-wojcicki/ |access-date=August 11, 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en |archive-date=October 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025174639/https://www.forbes.com/profile/susan-wojcicki/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 16, 2014, ahead of taking her fifth maternity leave, she wrote an article in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' about the importance of paid maternity leave.<ref name=":2" /> She was often quoted talking about the importance of finding the balance between family and career.

In addition to her American citizenship,<ref name=":3" /> Wojcicki held Polish citizenship through her father.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kafka|first1=Peter|title=New YouTube Boss Susan Wojcicki Talks Talent, Music and M&A (Q&A)|url=http://recode.net/2014/08/12/new-youtube-boss-susan-wojcicki-talks-talent-music-and-ma-qa/|website=[[Recode|Re/code]]|access-date=December 16, 2014|date=August 12, 2014|archive-date=April 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417143437/http://recode.net/2014/08/12/new-youtube-boss-susan-wojcicki-talks-talent-music-and-ma-qa/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web |url = http://next.gazeta.pl/next/7,151003,21560668,prezes-youtube-wlasnie-przyjechala-do-polski-a-to-dopiero-poczatek.html#BoxBizImg |title = Prezes YouTube właśnie przyjechała do Polski. A to dopiero początek dość niesamowitej historii |last1 = Hirsch |first1 = Rafał |website = next.[[Gazeta.pl]] |date = March 28, 2017 |language = pl |access-date = March 28, 2017 |archive-date = May 16, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170516033536/http://next.gazeta.pl/next/7,151003,21560668,prezes-youtube-wlasnie-przyjechala-do-polski-a-to-dopiero-poczatek.html#BoxBizImg |url-status = live}}</ref>

On February 13, 2024, Wojcicki's son Marco Troper, a 19-year-old student at the [[University of California, Berkeley]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Graff |first=Amy |date=February 16, 2023 |title=Former YouTube CEO's son identified as student who died at UC Berkeley |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/family-mourns-student-died-uc-berkeley-18672739.php |work=SFGate |access-date=February 18, 2024 |archive-date=February 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240218044529/https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/family-mourns-student-died-uc-berkeley-18672739.php |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Livemint |date=February 18, 2024 |title='Tragedy is hard to sustain,' Former YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki's son dies at 19 |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/world/former-youtube-ceo-susan-wojcickis-son-marco-troper-drug-usage-uc-berkeley-us-drug-cases-11708222977888.html |access-date=February 18, 2024 |website=mint |language=en |archive-date=February 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240218044540/https://www.livemint.com/news/world/former-youtube-ceo-susan-wojcickis-son-marco-troper-drug-usage-uc-berkeley-us-drug-cases-11708222977888.html |url-status=live}}</ref> died of [[Combined drug intoxication|acute combined drug toxicity]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Parker |first=Jordan |date=April 23, 2024 |title=Son of former YouTube CEO died from drug overdose at UC Berkeley, officials say |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/drug-overdose-killed-uc-berkeley-student-son-19419447.php |access-date=April 30, 2024 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |archive-date=April 30, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240430143606/https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/drug-overdose-killed-uc-berkeley-student-son-19419447.php |url-status=live}}</ref>

Wojcicki died on August 9, 2024, at the age of 56, after living with [[non-small-cell lung cancer]] for two years.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Afshar |first=Paradise |date=2024-08-10 |title=Susan Wojcicki, former YouTube CEO, dies at 56 {{!}} CNN Business |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2024/08/10/business/susan-wojcicki-obit/index.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240810100727/https://edition.cnn.com/2024/08/10/business/susan-wojcicki-obit/index.html |archive-date=2024-08-10 |access-date=2024-08-15 |website=[[CNN]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Yoon |first1=John |last2=Isaac |first2=Mike |date=August 10, 2024 |title=Susan Wojcicki, Former Chief of YouTube, Dies at 56 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/10/business/susan-wojcicki-dies.html |access-date=August 10, 2024 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=August 10, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240810065534/https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/10/business/susan-wojcicki-dies.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=August 9, 2024 |title=Susan Wojcicki, Former YouTube CEO and Influential Google Exec, Dies at 56 |url=https://variety.com/2024/digital/news/susan-wojcicki-dead-youtube-ceo-google-exec-1236102629/ |access-date=August 10, 2024 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-date=August 10, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240810054204/https://variety.com/2024/digital/news/susan-wojcicki-dead-youtube-ceo-google-exec-1236102629/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Parker |first=Jordan |date=August 9, 2024 |title=Former YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki dead at age 56 |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/former-youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-dead-age-56-19632780.php |access-date=August 10, 2024 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |archive-date=August 10, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240810072407/http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/former-youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-dead-age-56-19632780.php |url-status=live }}</ref>

In November 2024, three months after her death, a final message prepared by Wojcicki was publicly released where she reflected on her career, highlighting the significance of creativity, collaboration, and adhering to core values in leadership.<ref>{{Cite web |last=|first=|title=From Susan |archive-date=Nov 25, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241125142306/https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/from-susan/|url=https://blog.youtube/inside-youtube/from-susan/ |access-date=Dec 13, 2024 |website=blog.youtube|language=en|date=Nov 25, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ajemian |first=Emma Hinchliffe,Nina |title=Susan Wojcicki shares a final message |url=https://fortune.com/2024/11/25/former-youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-shares-a-final-message-three-months-after-her-death-from-lung-cancer/ |access-date=2024-11-28 |website=Fortune |language=en}}</ref>

== Recognition ==
